  "prompt": "Why is The Sandman called 'sandman'?",
  "response": "\"The Sandman\" is called so because it draws from the mythological and folkloric figure of the same name. The Sandman is a character found in various European traditions, particularly in Germanic folklore. He is often depicted as a mystical or supernatural being who brings sleep and dreams by sprinkling magical sand into people's eyes.\n\nNeil Gaiman's *The Sandman* comic book series, published by DC Comics, reimagines this mythological figure in a modern and expansive context. In Gaiman's narrative, the Sandman, also known as Dream or Morpheus, is one of the Endless, a family of personifications of universal concepts like Death, Desire, and Destiny. Dream's role is to govern the realm of dreams and stories, making him a central figure in shaping the subconscious and imaginative experiences of both humans and other beings.\n\nThe name \"Sandman\" is retained in Gaiman's work as a nod to this folklore tradition, while the character's rich backstory and mythology elevate him far beyond the simple bedtime figure of the original tales. The title also evokes the themes of dreams, sleep, and the subconscious, which are central to the series.",
